    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading a manual for a cessna 172 and saw stuff about the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed? and why is it such a big deal if it gets blocked up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! The pitot tube measures airspeed by comparing the dynamic pressure of the airflow arriving at the aircraft to the ambient static pressure. The dynamic pressure is obtained when the air flowing into the pitot tube is converted into force, pressing against a diaphragm within the tube. This diaphragm type two pressure readings - dynamic (indicated) and static (ambient). A differential pressure indicator then converts these pressure differences into an airspeed reading for the pilot to see on the instrument. If the pitot tube gets blocked, it can no longer accurately measure dynamic pressure, leading to incorrect airspeed readings, which can be very dangerous for the flight's safety.",
      "source": "target",
